  "report": {
    "narrative": [
      "Fleet-wide health signals are mixed but the current inventory snapshot is small (4 hosts), so treat this as a triage-ranked sample rather than a complete fleet assessment. Within the sample, risk is concentrated in two outliers:\n\n1) chi-gpu-001 (training-a, gpu-node, status=degraded) is the highest-risk host, driven by very high CPU load (0.92) and memory pressure (0.88). This combination commonly maps to immediate user impact (slow jobs, instability, OOM/restarts, noisy-neighbor contention).\n\n2) dal-storage-017 (analytics-b, storage, status=warning) is the next-highest risk, driven by high disk pressure (0.73) and memory pressure (0.79). This is likely to manifest as elevated I/O latency, cache churn, or storage service degradation that can spill into many workloads.\n\nThe remaining sampled hosts (chi-gpu-002 and chi-login-001) look healthy with substantially lower combined pressure.\n\nWhat to investigate first:\n- Start with chi-gpu-001: confirm whether the degradation is workload-driven or node health (top processes/containers, OOM/swap activity, kernel logs, GPU errors if available, recent job placement). If instability is confirmed, drain to protect users.\n- Then dal-storage-017: check disk fullness vs IOPS/latency, filesystem/RAID/SMART errors, and top talkers; remediate before disk pressure cascades.\n\nBroader context: VictoriaMetrics indicates 72 instrumented hosts, but the provided preview does not include per-host health breakdown; re-run/expand fleet queries (and correlate with scheduler hotspots) to determine whether these issues are isolated or part of wider degradation."
    ],
